SIMPLE: evade
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Evade
<hw>E*vade"</hw> (<?/), <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Evaded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>.
<conjf>Evading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>evadere</ets>,
<ets>evasum</ets>, <ets>e</ets> out + <ets>vadere</ets> to go, walk: cf.
F. s'⟦eacute⟧vader. See <er>Wade</er>.]</ety> <def>To get away from by
artifice; to avoid by dexterity, subterfuge, address, or ingenuity; to
elude; to escape from cleverly; <as>as, to <ex>evade</ex> a blow, a
pursuer, a punishment; to <ex>evade</ex> the force of an
argument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The heathen had a method, more truly their own, of
<qex>evading</qex> the Christian miracles.</q>
<rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Evade
<hw>E*vade"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To escape; to slip
away; -- sometimes with <xex>from</xex>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Evading</xex>
from perils.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unarmed they might⟦br⟧
Have easily, as spirits <qex>evaded</qex> swift⟦br⟧
By quick contraction or remove.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To attempt to escape; to practice artifice or
sophistry, for the purpose of eluding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ministers of God are not to <qex>evade</qex> and take refuge
any of these . . . ways.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To equivocate; shuffle. See
<er>Prevaricate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evadible</ent>⟦br⟧
